<br>
You have an MA in History and simple reading comprehension escapes you so often? Fkin, I didn’t say that you couldn’t agree with me. I said don’t agree with me if you won’t back it up well. I was specifically referring to a passage where your logic was essentially “Yer wrong, so there. Nyer,”.<br>
<br>
As to my minor in Theology, I mention it simply because my oh-so-secular university did not offer a degree in Theology, else I would’ve taken it. As to you having taken philosophy courses, good for you. Unfortunately they obviously did not work. Before you decide that you are a philosopher because you’ve taken a course or two, remember something important that an old friend of mine was fond of saying. “Just because you drive a truck, it don’t make you a trucker, and just because you hand someone a letter, it don’t make you a mailman.” <br>
<br>
So far, the only shred of evidence I’ve seen that you’ve ever set foot in a philosophy classroom was your (incorrect) usage of “ad hominem”. That’s first year Critical Thinking stuff, Fkin. How much philosophy work could you have done if you cannot understand the difference between a religion and a philosophy, between the trappings of faith and the faith itself? Try and see beyond face value for a change, or just give it a rest.<br>
<br>
&gt;I would also say the since the various followers of the various Hindo gods keep statues of the god they worship, adorn their bodies with decorations depending on which god they worship (such as the lines painted or tatooed on if you worship Vishnu), and lastly the differing precepts followed depending on which god you follow very definitely shows that these gods are worshipped for what they represent and not as a mask. <br>
<br>
You are beginning to show a pattern of not paying attention. Did I talk about practice? No, I talked about the underlying philosophy and theology that exists within, behind, and surrounding the Hindu belief system. Do not confuse ritual with belief, or theology with observational psychology. Bikers tattoo Harley logos on their arms. They aren’t monks. Baseball fans adorn their bodies with decorations based on what team they follow. They aren’t priests. These are trappings.<br>
<br>
&gt;It is also clear that you feel free to discount widely used concepts if they dont agree with your own twisted logic. I am sorry but its VERY clear that Buddism falls under the definition of religion, and unlike YOUR definition my definition has an actual basis in not only conventional definition and usage but actual accepted meaning. Sure I am sure you have your own radical splinter group beliefs, and much like the flat earth people you are willing to argue your view and muddy the discussion with various broad statements of psuedo fact, but the fact remains, in many cases I addressed all of your points with references and examples, you never responded with much in the way of anything past generalities.<br>
<br>
Comparing me to Flat Earthers? Nice ad hominem, Slick. Still, Flat Earthers can be a helluva lot of fun.<br>
<br>
Actually, my definition was set early in the discussion to separate a belief system with godhead from a belief system without godhead. If you look in a generic dictionary and find a simple definition that satisfies you, please do not expect someone else to accept it when they choose to speak more precisely about the topic than you do. I am not interested in intellectual laziness, and will not coddle such simply because you choose to regard a simplistic, pluralist, and basic definition as the gospel. <br>
<br>
If you look at your doctor and tell her, “My arm hurts”, she is going to ask you to be more specific. This is the same idea. You say religion and expect it to cover every single faith out there, yet your definition is so poor that sports can be considered religions. Your definition is too broad, get over it. Nothing is twisted about defining something more precisely.<br>
<br>
Insofar as not responding with anything but generalities, what do you call my questions?  Where are your facts, Fkin?<br>
<br>
&amp;#61656; I also have visited Buddhist temples in the Seattle area and listen to the Dahli Lama speak on two separate occasions there. It simply amazes me that one person can seriously disregard the actual definition of a word, the conventional usage, and the accepted typical meaning of a word (in this case religion) and propose their own radically different definition and expect to be taken seriously - astounding. Again, Buddhism and its practice is filled with references to temples, monks and monestaries and it is considered a religion and a religious way of life inherent in its very definition. Again - straight from the dictionary - note well point 2.<br>
<br>
Reread the definition and my deconstruction of it. It is too broad. Football is not a religion, but it is pursued with zeal and dedication. Colleges are called temples of learning, but are not religious institutes. Prison are institutions, but prisoners are not monks. You confuse the trappings of religion with religion.<br>
<br>
&gt;1 The teaching of Buddha that life is permeated with suffering caused by desire, that suffering ceases when desire ceases, and that enlightenment obtained through right conduct, wisdom, and meditation releases one from desire, suffering, and rebirth. <br>
<br>
Yes, agreed. I can scour the net for quotes from the Buddha too. Unlike you, when I post them, I actually try to explain how they relate to the discussion at hand.<br>
<br>
&gt;2 The religion represented by the many groups, especially numerous in Asia, that profess varying forms of this doctrine and that venerate Buddha. <br>
<br>
/sigh<br>
You are not paying attention again. Reverence is not worship. There is a difference. I can revere Winston Churchill as a great speaker and great man. I can revere his teachings. This does not mean that I worship him. The Buddha is treated similarly in the texts. He was a great man and deserves reverence. He was not a godhead.<br>
<br>
Do me a favor, please. Next time that you decide that I, or one of the many other people around here that you’ve accused of the same crime, “miss the point”, explain it. While there is no evidence of it hereabouts, you might actually have a valid point about this issue. I’d hate to think that there is a good idea buried deep inside you and it cannot escape because of oppressor Bulvai.<br>
