I cannot believe that you are so crass as to attempt to support your points with these blurbs from what is essentially &quot;Everything you wanted to know about Hinduism in one easy lesson&quot;. Show some respect, man.<br>
<br>
Sitting on a shelf above my desk as I type this is a book titled &quot;A Survey on hinduism&quot; by Klaus Klostermaier (ISBN 0-88706-809-X). It's a damned good book, about 650 pages long of small type. 650 pages, and it is a &quot;survey&quot;. I will use this text to quote from as it is very understandable. Please understand also that I am entering these notes by hand, not simply cutting and pasting from some poor pastiche of basic world religion.<br>
<br>
Let's try a quote from this source from page 125 - &quot;About a score of different Sanskrit words are rendered by the one English word God&quot; (please note that this follows up nicely on my earlier arguemtn about the generic nature of the English word &quot;God&quot;), &quot;We have to look at some of them in order to find out how the Hindus can at one and the same time have many gods and believe in One God&quot;<br>
<br>
Same page - &quot;F. Max Miller was struck by the evident fact that in a number of hymns the god to whom the song was addressed was praised as the only one, the supreme, the greatest, and that praise was not restricted to one and the same god, but given to various gods in various hymns. This did not conform to the classical notion of polytheism, so Muller coined the new term henotheism (from the Greek term henos, = &quot;one&quot;),&quot;<br>
<br>
Various gods are called the supreme and only god in different hymns. This is because those various gods are all the same, as we will see in later quotes.<br>
<br>
Page 127 - &quot;Much more important than the variable figure of the Deva (Roy note - Deva is used to refer to any number of celestial entities) was the basic underlying potency of which the Devas were only expressions and manifestations,&quot;<br>
<br>
In my previous argument, I used the term &quot;masks&quot; for simplicity.<br>
<br>
The text goes on to talk of Indra as High god on page 128 &quot;Only if Indra is understood as a symbol and manifestation of the High God do the attributes given to him makes sense, especially since the same attributes are given to various Devas, the same deeds are ascribed to  Agni, to Soma, to Varuna and others. (Roy note: quotes here appear in the text) &quot;They call him Indra, Mitra, Varuna, Agni, and he is heavenly winged Garutman. To what is One, sages give many a title.&quot;. Indra is only one of the names of the Savior God. The Supreme was first, and only under specific circumstances did he receive the name of Indra. The Supreme is nameless; men give names to him, variously describing him in categories taken from cosmic events, from history, or from their own experience,&quot;<br>
<br>
The same god keeps having different names throughout the history of the religion. The people realize this, yet still worship their own particular mask on the One God.<br>
<br>
Page 132 quotes the Upanisad, likely as important a work to the Hindus as the Bible is to Christians - &quot;In a dialogue, in the Brhadarankaya-Upanisad, Yajnavalkya is asked the crucial question, the &quot;kati devah&quot;. How many are the Devas? His first answer is a quotation from the Vedic text, &quot;Three hundred and three and three thousand and three.&quot; Pressed on, he reduces the number first to thirty three, then to six, then to three, to two, to one and a half, and finally to one. Asked Which is the one Deva? he answer, &quot;The Prajna (Roy note: breath, life). The Brahman. He is called Tyat (Roy Note: that).&quot;<br>
<br>
Later on the same page - &quot;Brahman, untranslatable, identified with the soul of everything, with the creator and maintainer, of the world, with the inner principle of the universe - Brahman becomes the word around which the loftiest religious speculation has revolved for thousands of years, and is still the term for the supreme being.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Brahman is the sole &quot;entity&quot; extent in the Hindu faith. All else are but shadows, mask, symbols, and manifestations.<br>
<br>
(Fkin)&gt;&quot;One of the principal Hindu deities, worshiped as the protector and preserver of worlds. Vishnu is often conceived as a member of the triad including also Brahma and Shiva.&quot;<br>
<br>
From page 133 - &quot;Hindu texts do indeed speak of the triad (Roy note: Also called the Trimurti) of Brahma as the creator, Visnu as the preserver, and Siva as the destroyer, fulfilling all the functions of the One God, but all those texts belong to to one of the traditions in which the Supreme is identical with one of those names and the three seperate names are but different aspects of the same being.&quot;<br>
<br>
This quote needs no explanation as to how it counters the article you quoted. How can you possibly think that anything so simple would possess any of the depth due a tradition as old as Hinduism?<br>
<br>
I am mortified that you would seek to boil down the world's oldest religion into &quot;Hinduism for Dummies&quot;, and then present it as support.<br>
<br>
