My point is that i gave my reasons why the law adding the phrase &quot;under god&quot; wasnt unconstitutional (first post).  The only counter argument provided was the courts didnt see it that way.  A decision by courts hardly prohibits a minority viewpoint internal to that institution.  clearly i support that minority viewpoint.<br>
<br>
the law in question is 50 years old.  During that time the related ammendments in the constitution have not changed.  It seems we were all living unconstitutionally for 50 years and nobody noticed.  Or atleast thats how it seems when its portrayed as &quot;clearly&quot; unconstitutional.  Or is it that the culture of america is changing? <br>
<br>
Now bout the 9th circuit.  Do you know that in recent history the 9th circuit court has MORE overturned rulings as all the ALL the other circuit courts COMBINED.  Their majority judgement can hardly be construed as perfect.  <br>
<br>
The senate supported 99-0 a resolution disagreeing with the 9th circuit.  Further there is a dissenting opinion. And the court under 9th circuit had the view:<br>
&quot;the lower court's decision to throw out the case found that &quot;the ceremonial reference to God in the pledge does not convey endorsement of particular religious beliefs&quot; <br>
All found here:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2002/LAW/06/26/pledge.allegiance/">www.cnn.com/2002/LAW/06/2...llegiance/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
AND YET.  when i gave the board reasons why the pledge of allegiance was constitutional it was dismissed as the court didnt see it that way with no real contention of the point.  I do expect the supreme court to see it the way i posted.  that the law supported no establishment therefor its not unconstitutional.  it gives face to an abstract moral authority titled &quot;god&quot;  with no more religion then your insurance clause that says &quot;act of god&quot;.  monotheist perhaps in cultural history but generic in use.   The senator that sponsored the change said on meet the press in 1954 the key reason was to highlight what is different about the US as compared to the soviet union.  Under god.  under a moral authority.  generic.  no reference to a &quot;respecting an establishment of religion&quot;<br>
<br>
As for the overall thrust of my intial post i borrowed much of it from a speech by a republican senator from georgia to be honest.  A speech he gave in the senate presented on CSPAN. i watch CSPAN while i play if something interesting is going on.  I except his points as my own after i thought bout them.  They are valid.  This ruling will be struck down by the supreme court.  Though the law one day maybe changed in congress.<br>
